  "prompt": "The parts of a motherboard, what they do and how they work?",
  "response": "Here's a comprehensive overview of motherboard components:\n\n1. CPU Socket\n- Connects the processor to the motherboard\n- Enables communication between CPU and other components\n- Provides power and data transfer\n- Varies in design based on processor type (Intel/AMD)\n\n2. RAM Slots\n- Insert memory modules\n- Provide temporary high-speed data storage\n- Faster access than hard drive storage\n- Support different memory types (DDR3, DDR4)\n\n3. Chipset\n- Central communication hub\n- Manages data flow between CPU, RAM, and peripherals\n- Contains two main parts:\n- Northbridge (memory controller)\n- Southbridge (slower peripheral connections)\n\n4. BIOS/UEFI Chip\n- Stores firmware instructions\n- Initializes hardware during boot process\n- Contains motherboard configuration settings\n- Provides low-level system management\n\n5. Power Connectors\n- 24-pin ATX connector (main power)\n- 4/8-pin CPU power connector\n- Distribute electrical power from power supply\n- Regulate voltage for different components\n\n6. PCIe Slots\n- Expand system capabilities\n- Connect graphics cards\n- Support sound cards, network adapters\n- Different generations with increasing bandwidth\n\n7. SATA Ports\n- Connect storage devices\n- Support hard drives and SSDs\n- Transfer data between storage and system\n\n8. M.2 Slots\n- High-speed storage connections\n- Support NVMe and SATA SSDs\n- Compact, direct motherboard integration\n\n9. Expansion Slots\n- Allow additional hardware installation\n- Support various peripheral cards\n\n10. I/O Ports\n- External connection points\n- USB, audio, network, video interfaces\n- Enable peripheral device connections\n\nEach component plays a crucial role in system functionality, communication, and performance.",
